BusyBox is a software suite that integrates many common Unix utilities into a single, small executable, often referred to as "The Swiss Army Knife of Embedded Linux". It is designed for resource-constrained environments like embedded devices and minimal Linux distributions. Due to its compact nature, BusyBox acts as a "multi-call binary," meaning a single executable can perform the functions of various utilities based on how it's invoked.

When `busybox wget` is executed, BusyBox interprets "wget" as an "applet" and carries out its `wget` functionality. This BusyBox version of `wget` is a lightweight implementation, and it typically offers fewer options and features compared to the full-featured GNU `wget` utility. For instance, certain BusyBox `wget` versions may lack support for all security features, HTTPS redirects, or specific options like `--no-directories`."""
