    name='search',
    response={
      'result': """ConPot, an open-source honeypot, includes built-in support for the Kamstrup protocol, enabling it to emulate Kamstrup smart meters. This functionality is part of ConPot's protocol modules and encompasses both the Kamstrup management protocol and the meter protocol.

Specifically, ConPot's `conpot.protocols.kamstrup` package contains subpackages for `management_protocol` and `meter_protocol`. These modules allow ConPot to respond to Kamstrup commands, simulating a real smart meter, and can even provide realistic changes in power usage.

The Kamstrup Meter Protocol (KMP) is utilized by various Kamstrup utility meters, such as the MULTICAL 403, to read measurements. This protocol facilitates communication via an optical interface present on these meters, often requiring a UART bus with a baud rate of 1200 and 2 stop bits for communication. The KMP is designed for point-to-point communication and is common across Kamstrup consumption meters introduced from 2006 onwards.

Kamstrup smart meters also commonly use the DLMS/COSEM data collection protocol as a system integration interface, ensuring a standardized approach for communication with Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems. Additionally, Kamstrup meters support various communication technologies, including Wireless M-Bus, GSM, GPRS, Wi-Fi, ZigBee, and Z-Wave.

The development of ConPot's Kamstrup emulation was highlighted by The Honeynet Project, noting its ability to pose as a smart meter to investigate malicious actions against these devices. They also mentioned a telnet-based management protocol running on port 50100 for Kamstrup meters, which allows for changing system settings. The ConPot team has even participated in events like BruCon to release new versions and discuss upcoming improvements, including further decoding and responding to Kamstrup commands."""
    }
  )
